# Project Context
You are an expert front-end developer building a side project with Next.js (App Router), TypeScript, and Tailwind CSS. The project uses a lightweight, customized Feature-Sliced Design (FSD) architecture.

# Architecture Rules (Custom FSD)
Strictly respect the following custom folder structure under `src/`. Do not create arbitrary top-level folders.

- `src/app/`: Next.js App Router. Contains only routing and layouts.
- `src/widgets/`: Independent layouts that combine multiple features (e.g., IssueList, Header).
- `src/features/`: Independent, user-facing functionality units (e.g., issue-card, issue-filter, issue-timeline).
- `src/entities/`: Domain models, business logic, API mutations/queries, and global state (e.g., issue/api.ts, issue/types.ts, issue/store.ts using TanStack Query and Zustand).
- `src/shared/`: Reusable, project-wide components and utilities (e.g., ui/, lib/, config/).

### Layer Dependency Rules
- Allowed Direction: `app` â†’ `widgets` â†’ `features` â†’ `entities` â†’ `shared`
- Upper layers can only import from lower layers.
- `shared` must never import from any other layer.
- Avoid direct imports between slices in the same layer. Combine them in `widgets` or `app` if needed.

### Path Aliases
- Use absolute paths: `@/`, `@widgets/`, `@features/`, `@entities/`, `@shared/`

# Code Generation Guidelines
- No 'any' Type: Never use the 'any' type under any circumstances. Ensure everything is strictly typed.
- Styling & Class Names: Always use the `cn` utility function located at `src/shared/lib/cn.ts` for conditional Tailwind CSS classes (combining `clsx` and `tailwind-merge`). Do not use `clsx` or `tailwind-merge` directly.

# Semantic Markup & Web Accessibility (Strict)
- Publisher-Level HTML: Prioritize semantic HTML elements over meaningless `div` tags. Use `main`, `nav`, `header`, `footer`, `article`, `section`, `aside`, `figure`, `time`, etc., according to their intended purpose. Avoid using `div` for layout or styling unless no semantic alternative exists.
- Accessibility (ARIA): Interactive elements must be keyboard-navigable and meet WCAG 2.1 AA contrast standards. Include appropriate ARIA attributes (`aria-label`, `aria-live`, `role`) when native semantics are insufficient.
- Specific Implementation Examples for this Project:
  - Issue Card: Use `<article>` + `<time datetime="...">`.
  - 3-Line Summary: Use `<ol>` (ordered context) + `aria-label` for each item (e.g., `aria-label="1ë‹¨ęł„: ..."`).
  - Filter Tabs: Use `role="tablist"` + `role="tab"` + `aria-selected="..."`.
  - Live Update Areas: Use `aria-live="polite"`.
- Interactive Elements: Prioritize native interactive elements like `<button>` or `<a>`. Ensure form `label` elements are properly connected.